CCII.Fieri potest ut per fractos radious videatur quippiam, quod per rectos in conspectum venire non potest. Perspectiva communis 7.p.3. CCIII. Hoc experientia cognoscitur de qua monet Euclides 7. Hypothesi catoptricorum, quae sola non catoptrica sed mesoptica est nec quiquam praeter hanc hypothesin mesopticum habet. Si enim res aliqua in vas iniiciatur, et ab oculo recedat vas quoad res in fundo posita cerni non possit, eam inquit visum ira ab eadem remotione, si aquae in vas infundantur. CCIIII Huiusmodi fallacia decepti astronomi aliquando stellam esse supra finitorem arbitrantur, quae adhuc est infra, quod in luminaris [NB Veneris in printed text] observatione quibusdam accidisse legimus, imo orto solis vel lunae solum [NB tantum in printed text] segmento aliquo [NB minore in printed text] maxima fallacia fieri potest, ut totus sol vel [NB tota in printed text] luna supra finitorem esse videatur. Eodemque modo in occasu accidit [NB accidere potest in printed text] ut totum adhuc superesse esse
text translation: And thus Athagenus 16.n.7. Vitello 50.p.10. Common perspective 8.p.3. They have erred in establishing that the heavens are thinner than air, clearer, and more subtle. 102. It is possible that something may be seen through broken rays of light that through straight rays cannot come into view. Common perspective 7.p.3. 103. This is known by experiment, which Euclid makes known in the seventh hypothesis of his Catoptrica, which [hypothesis] alone is not catoptric but rather mesoptic, nor does he [Euclid] have anything mesoptic other than this hypothesis. For if something is thrown into a container, and the container withdraws from the eye to the point where the thing positioned on its bottom is no longer visible, he says that this [very object] will be seen from the same distance, if water is poured into the container. 104. Deceived by a trick of this sort, astronomers sometimes judge there to be a star above the horizon [? finitor], which in fact is beneath it. I read that this can happen to certain people in the observation of a heavenly body—at the first rising of the sun or of the moon a great deception is able to arise from just a segment [of either body], so that the whole sun or moon appears above the horizon [? finitor]. Indeed it is able to happen in the same way at the setting [of sun or moon], so that the whole [body appears] still to remain [in the sky]

text: Ex epistola D. Thomae Smithi ad D. Gualteru[m] Haddonu[m] de huius libri argumento et usu. Quia n[ost]ram rempub. absens desidero, de eadem tres libros Tholosae conscripsi, quibus titulu[m] feci de repub: Angloru[m]. In quibus totam fere formam eius explicui: praesertim in illis rebus ubi caeteris differt. Differt autem fere in omnibus: ita ut opus longius progressu[m] sit quam putabam. Scripsi autem sermone nostrati: stilo inter historicum et philosophicum medio, ad eam forma[m] qua scripsisse coniectabam Aristotelem de multis greciae rebus pub: qui libri non nunc excideru[n]t. Prebui argumentu[m] uberrimu[m] illis, qui disputare philosophico more de singulis quaestionibus volunt: et problemata facere, aequu[m]ne an iniquum sit; et utru[m] sit melius, id quod istic teneatur in Anglia pro lege, an quod hic, et in illis prouinciis, quae Romano jure reguntur.
text translation: From the epistle of doctor Thomas Smith to doctor Walter Haddon, concerning the argument and use of this book: Because I long for our commonwealth while absent, I have written three books on it at Toulouse, to which I have affixed the title On the Commonwealth of the English. In them I have explicated almost its entire form, especially in those things where it differs from other [governments]. However, it differs in almost everything: so that this work has progressed for longer than I thought. I wrote [the book] in our language, in a style midway between the historical and the philosophical—in the form in which I inferred that Aristotle had written on many of the Greek commonwealths. These [i.e. Aristotle’s] books have now perished. I have provided most fruitful argument for those who wish to dispute in a philosophical fashion concerning particular questions, and to construct problems: concerning what is just or unjust, and whether what is held for law there in England, or what is used here, and in those provinces which are ruled by Roman law, is better.
book title: De republica Anglorum. The maner of Governement or policie of the Realme of England

anchor text translation: [Epicurus wrote the following noble sentiment, urging] that he make Pythocles rich not in a public nor in a hazardous manner. If you wish (he says) to make Pythocles wealthy, you do not need to add to his stock of money but rather subtract from his stock of desires. If you wish that he be honorable, you don't need to add to his honors, but substract from his desires. If you wish that Pythocles be engaged in every kind of pleasure, you don't need to add to his pleasures, but subtract from his desires. [If you wish to make him an old man and give him a full life, you don't need to add to his years, but subtract from his desires].
